{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17650226","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17650226"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:10:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:10:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18396"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18396"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.68,0.14,0.11,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11114"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114289"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11114"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18396"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96289"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"8512"},{"type":"tags","id":"10260"},{"type":"tags","id":"10275"},{"type":"tags","id":"10292"},{"type":"tags","id":"11274"},{"type":"tags","id":"11275"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25766"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25770"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114289"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the neuromuscular cleft?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gap between sensory neuron and muscle fibre","Gap between motor neuron and muscle fibre","Gap between mixed neuron and muscle fibre","It is not a gap","Gap between interneuron and muscle fibre"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe neuromuscular junction is a critical site where nerve impulses are transmitted from motor neurons to muscle fibres, leading to muscle contraction. This process involves the release of neurotransmitters into a specific gap. The \u003Cstrong\u003Egap between motor neuron and muscle fibre\u003C/strong\u003E is known as the neuromuscular cleft. This is the space where neurotransmitters, such as acetylcholine, are released from the motor neuron to bind to receptors on the muscle fibre, initiating muscle contraction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGap between sensory neuron and muscle fibre\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as sensory neurons do not directly synapse with muscle fibres. \u003Cstrong\u003EGap between mixed neuron and muscle fibre\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because mixed neurons contain both sensory and motor fibres but do not directly synapse with muscle fibres. \u003Cstrong\u003EIt is not a gap\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the neuromuscular cleft is indeed a gap. \u003Cstrong\u003EGap between interneuron and muscle fibre\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because interneurons are located within the central nervous system and do not directly synapse with muscle fibres.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The neuromuscular cleft is the gap between the motor neuron and the muscle fibre.","The neuromuscular junction is where the motor neuron communicates with the muscle fibre to initiate contraction.","Acetylcholine is the neurotransmitter released into the neuromuscular cleft to stimulate muscle contraction."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 7; pg. 93","Patton KT, Thibodeau GA. Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2018.","Hutson M, Ward A, editors. Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press; 2015.","Longo UG, Denaro V, editors. Textbook of musculoskeletal disorders. Springer Nature; 2023.","Hughes SH. The Musculoskeletal System: The Musculoskeletal System-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2022.","Frontera WR, Ochala J. Skeletal muscle: a brief review of structure and function. Calcif Tissue Int. 2015 Mar;96(3):183-95.","Morrison BM. Neuromuscular Diseases. Semin Neurol. 2016 Oct;36(5):409-418."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96289"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18396"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96289"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T14:44:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T14:44:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11114"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114289"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":